body: @snnn I believe we are still blocked on this issue, could you please re-open and point us to a resource that could help us address this build issue?

Some additional information: while build.py script is executed, it tries to install some packages from python (particularly numpy) using `python.exe -m pip install setuptools wheel numpy` and so on, logs show that all components are already installed. But when it starts cmake build script (CMakeLists) It cannot find Numpy component on the following line
`find_package(Python 3.6 COMPONENTS Interpreter Development.Module NumPy)`. I wrote PYTHON_EXECUTABLE immediatly after the line and it shows correct path to python.exe. It looks like cmake search numpy in correct place but do not find it

If you have installed numpy but cmake can't find it, it is either a dev environment setup problem or a bug of cmake. It is not a bug of onnxruntime. To debug it, you will need to look at cmake's logs files. You can find them in your build folder. If nothing helps, usually I would open cmake's *.cmake source files and add print statements there.  For example,  add
```
message("XXXXXXXXXXX")
```
to https://github.com/Kitware/CMake/blob/master/Modules/FindPython.cmake.

cmake doesn't come with a debugger. So I use this way to figure what's going on. 

If you can reproduce this problem with a minimal example, for example create a sample cmake project with just 
```
find_package(Python 3.6 COMPONENTS Interpreter Development.Module NumPy)
```
If it still fails, you can report it to the cmake community where you may get better support, because they are the specialist of cmake.

Thanks @snnn! I understand all your statements and I have been trying to investigate cmake scripts in suggested way.
If it is environment problem what do you think about way to check it? May be reinstall cmake, python, VS Community and onnxruntime as result?

I build onnxruntime on windows every two weeks with no issues. I use python 3.9 (onnx on python 3.10 has not been released yet). I never have python path in environment variable %PATH%, i add it when i need it. I use the standard python distribution (not anaconda). I rarely have issues.
Thanks for comments @xadupre! I think python should be in PATH due to during ONNX Runtime build the python script (build.py) is launched. May be it is python version issue, I should check
I mean i add python path to PATH but it is only valid for the command line window i opened to run the build. Without adding it, it fails but that's how i check there is not other python.
python doesn't have to be in PATH when build.py is invoked.

Hello guys! Thanks for your help! I've resolved problem locally by hardcoded direct path to numpy to special cmake key (Python_NumPy_INCLUDE_DIR) before find_package(Python ...). In my understanding it is weird behavior of find_package method for python on CMake side. I continue to investigate CMake script for problem localization.

Notes for other readers: Python downgrading to 3.9 version, VS Community and CMake reinstalling did not help to solve the issue.
